    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - May 3, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🪖 The Pentagon invited seven AI vendors into the classified room and left Anthropic outside\n\nDefense procurement has found its model selector. Naturally, it is classified.\n\n- **The deals:** AP reported on May 1 that Google, Microsoft, AWS, Nvidia, OpenAI, Reflection and SpaceX reached agreements to put AI tools on U.S. military classified networks.\n- **The absence:** Anthropic was not included after its fight with the Trump administration over military AI use, safety limits and a federal ban.\n- **The direction:** the Pentagon framed the rollout as support for faster battlefield decision-making, intelligence work and logistics.\n\n*The consumer chatbot era was cute. The procurement era has badges and consequences.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/060cecf836c4cebcf012a3ceb5333f2c) | [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/01/pentagon-inks-deals-with-nvidia-microsoft-and-aws-to-deploy-ai-on-classified-networks/)\n\n---\n\n## 🌊 The Navy wants AI minehunters for Hormuz, because shipping lanes now need MLOps\n\nThe Strait of Hormuz file has upgraded from naval headache to sensor-fusion procurement exercise.\n\n- **The contract:** Reuters reported on May 1 that the U.S. Navy awarded Domino Data Lab a contract worth up to $99.7 million for Project AMMO.\n- **The job:** the software is meant to help unmanned underwater vehicles detect new Iranian mine types using side-scan sonar, visual imaging and model monitoring.\n- **The speed claim:** Domino says mine-detection model updates could move from as long as six months to days.\n\n*Mine-hunting used to be steel, sailors and patience. Now it also needs a deployment pipeline.*\n\n**Sources:** [Defense News and Reuters](https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2026/05/01/us-navy-turns-to-ai-firm-domino-for-options-to-counter-iranian-mines/) | [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/artificial-intelligence/us-navy-signs-deal-with-ai-firm-for-training-underwater-drones-to-detect-mines-in-strait-of-hormuz-usd100-million-would-allow-drone-minesweepers-to-update-their-detection-algorithms-in-days-instead-of-months)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 Meta bought humanoid robot brains, because the feed apparently needed legs\n\nMeta has spent years teaching software to predict humans. The next trick is giving that obsession elbows.\n\n- **The acquisition:** TechCrunch reported on May 1 that Meta acquired Assured Robot Intelligence for an undisclosed sum.\n- **The team:** ARI co-founders Lerrel Pinto and Xiaolong Wang will join Meta Superintelligence Labs with expertise in robot control and self-learning.\n- **The target:** ARI was building foundation models for humanoid robots doing physical labor, including household chores.\n\n*If AGI needs a body, Big Tech will make sure the body arrives through M&A.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/01/meta-buys-robotic-startup-to-bolster-its-humanoid-ai-ambitions/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 1X opened the NEO factory and promised the home robot spreadsheet will behave\n\nThe humanoid market has reached the manufacturing-plan phase, which is where demos meet rent.\n\n- **The factory:** 1X said its Hayward, California NEO Factory spans 58,000 square feet and employs more than 200 people.\n- **The capacity:** the company says Hayward can produce up to 10,000 NEOs per year, with San Carlos meant to help scale toward 100,000-plus annually by late 2027.\n- **The delivery line:** 1X says consumer deliveries are still planned to begin in 2026.\n\n*The useful robot is no longer just a video. It is now a supply-chain promise, which is scarier in a different way.*\n\n**Sources:** [1X](https://www.1x.tech/discover/neo-factory) | [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-30/humanoid-maker-1x-opens-us-factory-plans-to-make-10-000-home-robots-this-year)\n\n---\n\n## 🗣️ xAI shipped Grok 4.3 and made voice cloning another pricing war\n\nThe model race has found a new knob to turn: cheaper tokens, louder audio, more awkward demos.\n\n- **The release:** VentureBeat reported on May 1 that xAI launched Grok 4.3 and a web-based Custom Voices cloning suite.\n- **The API price:** OpenRouter lists Grok 4.3 at $1.25 per million input tokens and $2.50 per million output tokens.\n- **The angle:** VentureBeat framed the release as a push to undercut rivals while xAI tries to regain momentum after researcher departures and stronger competing models.\n\n*Nothing says stable frontier lab like a discount model and a voice clone in the same news cycle.*\n\n**Sources:** [VentureBeat](https://venturebeat.com/technology/xai-launches-grok-4-3-at-an-aggressively-low-price-and-a-new-fast-powerful-voice-cloning-suite/) | [OpenRouter](https://openrouter.ai/x-ai/grok-4.3)\n"
  }
